<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1687,2038]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,376,1688,1714]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Material examined</emphasis>
. 
<typeStatus box="[389,494,1688,1714]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Syntypes</typeStatus>
, male, pupa [with female inside] and 
<specimenCount box="[905,996,1688,1714]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="larva">2 larvae</specimenCount>
, reared from galls on aerial root of 
<taxonomicName authority="Bl." authorityName="Bl." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Strobilanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cernua">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Strobilanthes cernua</emphasis>
Bl.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[397,544,1724,1751]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Acanthaceae</taxonomicName>
) collected at Mt Gede, Cibodas, 
<collectingRegion box="[920,972,1725,1751]" country="Indonesia" name="Jawa Timur" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Java</collectingRegion>
, alt. 
<quantity box="[1028,1117,1724,1751]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="m" value="1800.0">1800 m</quantity>
, 
<date box="[1130,1228,1724,1750]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" value="1918-12">xii-1918</date>
, Felt #a3097. One slide bears the male, the other the remainder of the series. The male is well-preserved, all legs entire, wings slightly folded, one antenna with remaining 7, the other with 6 flagellomeres, and terminalia in posterior position. The pupa and the female inside it are well-preserved. One of the larvae is cleared, the other uncleared.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1687,2038]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1868,1894]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Description</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[352,410,1868,1894]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Male</emphasis>
. Length 
<quantity box="[510,577,1868,1895]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
, wing length 
<quantity box="[729,817,1868,1895]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="3.8">3.8 mm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity box="[900,989,1868,1895]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="1.4">1.4 mm</quantity>
. Antenna: first flagellomere 5.5x longer than wide, sixth 4.5x [
<figureCitation box="[394,477,1903,1930]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 7e</figureCitation>
]. palpus 2-segmented, first segment short, irregular, second broadly oval. Apicoventral spur on first tarsal segment long, slightly bent [
<figureCitation box="[671,755,1939,1966]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 7c</figureCitation>
]. Tarsal claws strongly curved at distal third, empodia as long as claws, pulvilli about ¼ empodial length [
<figureCitation box="[639,725,1975,2002]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 7d</figureCitation>
]. Gonostylus 2x longer than wide in posterior view, teeth blunt, of slightly unequal length [
<figureCitation box="[452,539,2011,2038]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 7b</figureCitation>
].
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" startId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" targetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" targetPageId="16">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1620,1824]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,591,1620,1644]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
FIGURES 7a–n. 
<taxonomicName box="[334,591,1620,1644]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Asphondylia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strobilanthi">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[334,591,1620,1644]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Asphondylia strobilanthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
: a, galls on aerial root of 
<taxonomicName box="[847,1056,1620,1644]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Strobilanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cernua">
<emphasis box="[847,1056,1620,1644]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Strobilanthes cernua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1870,2041]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis box="[199,283,1870,1896]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Female</emphasis>
. Description based on specimen still inside its pupa. Flagellomeres 1–9 progressively slightly shorter, 10–12 progressively much shorter [
<figureCitation box="[543,628,1906,1933]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[596,628,1906,1933]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="7.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="g" value="7.0">7g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
], first flagellomere 5.5x longer than wide. Needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor slightly widened at terminus in ventral view [
<figureCitation box="[779,865,1942,1969]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 7h</figureCitation>
].
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1870,2041]" lastBlockId="17.[151,1437,150,934]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis box="[199,258,1979,2004]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Pupa</emphasis>
. Length 
<quantity box="[361,429,1978,2005]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
, thorax dark, abdomen dark yellow (
<bibRefCitation author="Felt, E. P." box="[846,974,1978,2005]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="139 - 151" refId="ref58163" refString="Felt, E. P. (1921 b) Javanese gall midges. Treubia, 1, 139 - 151." type="journal article" year="1921">Felt 1921b</bibRefCitation>
). Antennal horns long, triangular, serrate ventrally [
<figureCitation box="[265,359,2014,2041]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[318,359,2014,2041]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="m" value="7.0">7m</quantity>
</figureCitation>
]. Frontal anterior horn robust, bilobed, lobes pointed; posterior horns absent [
<figureCitation box="[1224,1318,2014,2041]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[1278,1318,2014,2041]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="m" value="7.0">7m</quantity>
</figureCitation>
]. Cephalic papillae minute [
<figureCitation box="[341,434,150,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[396,434,150,177]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="m" value="7.0">7m</quantity>
</figureCitation>
] Prothoracic spiracle unusually long, narrow, of constant width, trachea bulging, ending at basal fifth [
<figureCitation box="[305,384,186,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7l</figureCitation>
]. Abdominal dorsal spines simple, relatively small, arranged in sparse anterior field and dense posterior row, size of spines increasing posteriad [
<figureCitation box="[710,796,222,249]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7n</figureCitation>
].
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,150,934]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis box="[199,266,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Larva</emphasis>
. Length 
<quantity box="[373,466,258,285]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
. Yellowish orange. Head rounded, trapezoid, wider than long, antennae 1.5x longer than wide at base, posterolateral apodemes absent [
<figureCitation box="[729,810,294,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7i</figureCitation>
]. Spatula broad, short-shafted; with two long, narrowly triangular teeth separated by distance 3x greater than their basal width; on either side with 2 pairs of lateral setose papillae; no pigmented area around shaft [
<figureCitation box="[630,711,366,393]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7j</figureCitation>
]. Terminal segment with anus positioned ventrocaudally and no terminal papillae visible on available specimens [
<figureCitation box="[703,789,402,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7k</figureCitation>
].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,150,934]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,439,465]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[322,598,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Asphondylia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strobilanthi">
<emphasis box="[322,598,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Asphondylia strobilanthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique among its Indonesian congeners for the narrow, widely separated lobes of the larval sternal spatula [
<figureCitation box="[544,625,474,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7j</figureCitation>
], and, in the pupa, the long, tube-like prothoracic spiracle [
<figureCitation box="[1300,1380,474,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7l</figureCitation>
], the two-lobed anterior frontal horn, the lack of posterior frontal horns [
<figureCitation box="[925,1021,510,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[980,1021,510,537]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="m" value="7.0">7m</quantity>
</figureCitation>
], and the ventrally serrated antennal horns [
<figureCitation box="[227,322,546,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[281,322,546,573]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="m" value="7.0">7m</quantity>
</figureCitation>
]. It can be separated from Indonesian congeners whose males are known by the prolonged gonostylus [
<figureCitation box="[198,284,582,609]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7b</figureCitation>
].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,150,934]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,289,618,644]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Biology</emphasis>
. DvL (1921, 
<figureCitation box="[439,505,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 9" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1712,1736]" captionTargetBox="[160,1431,191,1681]" captionTargetId="figure-17@21.[151,1436,181,1688]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 9a–l. Asphoxenomyia smilacis: a–h, male: a, wing; b, palpus; c, basal part of antenna; d, 5th flagellomere; e, terminalia (lateral; arrows indicate aedeagus (ae), cercus (ce), gonocoxite (gc), gonostylus, (gs), hypoproct (hy)); f, first tarsomere; g, last tarsomere; h, tarsal claw of midleg with pulvillus and empodium; i–k, female: i, terminalia (lateral); j, basal part of antenna; k, 9th flagellomere; l, galls on Smilax modesta (Fig. 59 of DvLR &amp; DvL (1926))." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406878" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406878/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
[
<figureCitation box="[518,601,618,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 7" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[157,1432,188,1588]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1436,181,1596]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7a–n. Asphondylia strobilanthi: a, galls on aerial root of Strobilanthes cernua, cross section of single gall at bottom right (Fig. 9 of DvL (1921); b–e, male: b, gonostylus (posterior); c, first tarsal segment; d, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; e, sixth and seventh flagellomeres; f–h, female: f, last tarsal segment with claw, empodium and pulvillus; g, last flagellomeres; h, end of needle-like protrusible part of ovipositor; i–k, larva: i, head (dorsal); j, sternal spatula with adjacent papillae; k, end of body (dorsal); l–n, pupa: l, prothoracic spiracle; m, anterior segments (ventral); n, last three abdominal segments (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406874/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 7a</figureCitation>
]) described the gall on the aerial roots of 
<taxonomicName box="[1066,1299,619,645]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Strobilanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cernua">
<emphasis box="[1066,1299,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Strobilanthes cernua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a plant that grows gregariously in virgin forests on mountain sides [of Mt Gede, Cibodas, 
<collectingRegion box="[1018,1074,654,681]" country="Indonesia" name="Jawa Timur" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Java</collectingRegion>
]. Parts of the root develop above ground, which is where these were found, partly hidden under remains of leaves and patches of moss. They are galls of the bark, whose shape is either pyriform or more globular, stout and round at the base, and gradually narrowing towards the apex. The largest galls measured 
<quantity box="[660,740,763,789]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
in length, with a thickness of 
<quantity box="[1077,1145,763,789]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
. The usual size is smaller, being about 
<quantity box="[289,406,799,825]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="5.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="4.0">4 to 7 mm</quantity>
. The rind of the bark is thick and the chamber wide. The surface is densely pilose with long, white, unbranched hairs. Galls are found both singly and gregariously.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,150,934]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
